		<part id="landscapes">
			<title>What? Cultivate API Landscapes!</title>
			<slide id="managing-landscape-value">
				<title>API Landscape Value</title>
				<img src="API-value-landscape.png" class="fullsize"/>
			</slide>
			<slide id="landscape-challenges">
				<title>Challenges for API Landscapes</title>
				<ul>
					<li><em>Productization:</em> Manage all APIs by balancing autonomy and coordination</li>
					<li><em>Innovation:</em> Allow new patterns and practices to evolve</li>
					<li><em>Coordination:</em> Prevent bottlenecks created by centralized processes</li>
					<li><em>Stability:</em> Complex dependencies can create stability challenges</li>
					<li><em>Coherence:</em> Balance local vs. global optimization</li>
				</ul>
			</slide>
		</part>
		<part id="governance">
			<title>How? Observe, Harmonize, Support</title>
			<slide id="insights">
				<title>Observe with Insights: API the APIs</title>
				<img title="Food Labels" href="https://www.google.ch/search?q=food+labels&amp;tbm=isch" src="food-labels.png" style=" float: right ; width : 35% ; margin : 3% ; "/>
				<ul>
					<li>Make <em>introspection</em> part of the API landscape</li>
					<li>Combine decentralization with the ability for gaining insights</li>
					<li>APIs can be <q>described</q> in a variety of ways</li>
					<ul>
						<li><em>Technical descriptions</em> for interface mechanics (e.g., <a href="https://www.openapis.org/">OpenAPI</a>)</li>
						<li><em>Documentation</em> intended for human consumption</li>
						<li><em>Metadata</em> for API lifecycle management (e.g., <a href="https://schema.org/WebAPI">schema.org</a>)</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="api-visibility">
				<title>API Visibility: Inside-Out vs. Outside-In</title>
				<!-- this image is from API days paris 2019 -->
				<img src="portal-outside-inside.png" class="fullsize"/>
			</slide>
			<slide id="interfaces">
				<title>Harmonize with Interfaces: Provide Clear Guidance</title>
				<ul>
					<li>Aim for the <em>minimal number of constraints</em> for your API landscape</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Minimizing constraints maximizes the freedom of teams</li>
						<li>Revisit existing constraints and remove/relax them when possible</li>
					</ul>
					<li>Look at rules as <em>suggestions how to satisfy constraints</em></li>
					<ul>
						<li>Help teams to satisfy constraints if they want/need help</li>
						<li>Try to make rules optional whenever possible</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="nudging">
				<title>Support with Nudging: Help to do Things Right</title>
				<img src="prometheus-engineer.jpg" class="fullsize"/>
			</slide>
			<slide id="why-guidelines">
				<title>API Guidelines as Shared Practices</title>
				<ul>
					<li>Larger API landscapes mean more ways to solve the same problem</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Solving <q>API problems</q> is not what teams should focus on</li>
						<li>Solving <q>API problems</q> in a consistent way helps the API landscape</li>
					</ul>
					<li>Make it easy to <q>do the right thing</q> by providing support</li>
					<ul>
						<li>Tooling can validate APIs and increase <em>API product quality</em></li>
						<li>Tooling can simplify implementation and reduce <em>API time-to-market</em></li>
						<li>Tooling can help with consumption and increase <em>realized API value</em></li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="in-the-wild">
				<title>API Guidelines in the Wild</title>
				<img href="https://dret.github.io/guidelines/" title="API Guidelines in the Wild" src="api-guidelines.png" class="fullsize"/>
			</slide>
		</part>
